00:09:51.329 --> 00:10:00.040
All right, I’ve saved the best for last:
LUVOIR, or the Large UV/Optical/IR Surveyor.

00:10:00.040 --> 00:10:04.100
James Webb is going to be a powerful telescope,
but it’s an infrared instrument designed

00:10:04.100 --> 00:10:08.069
to look at cooler objects in the Universe,
like red-shifted galaxies at the beginning

00:10:08.069 --> 00:10:11.379
of time, or newly forming planetary systems.

00:10:11.379 --> 00:10:15.420
The Origins Space Telescope will be a better
version of James Webb.

00:10:15.420 --> 00:10:19.040
LUVOIR will be the true successor to the Hubble
Space Telescope.

00:10:19.040 --> 00:10:25.209
It’ll be a huge instrument capable of seeing
in infrared, visible light and ultraviolet.

00:10:25.209 --> 00:10:27.819
There are two designs in the works.

00:10:27.819 --> 00:10:32.769
One which is 8-meters across and could launch
on a heavy-lift vehicle like the Falcon Heavy.

00:10:32.769 --> 00:10:37.879
And another design that would use the Space
Launch System that measures 15-meters across.

00:10:37.879 --> 00:10:42.629
That’s 50% bigger than the biggest Earth-based
telescope.

00:10:42.629 --> 00:10:45.170
Remember, Hubble is only 2.6 meters.

00:10:45.170 --> 00:10:49.730
It’ll have a wide field of view and a suite
of filters and instruments that astronomers

00:10:49.730 --> 00:10:52.060
can use to observe whatever they want.

00:10:52.060 --> 00:10:55.760
It’ll be equipped with a coronograph like
we talked about earlier, to directly observe

00:10:55.760 --> 00:11:00.830
planets and obscure their stars, a spectrograph
to figure out what chemicals are present in

00:11:00.830 --> 00:11:03.620
exoplanet atmospheres, and more.

00:11:03.620 --> 00:11:08.370
LUVOIR will be a general purpose instrument,
which astronomers will use to make discoveries

00:11:08.370 --> 00:11:13.740
across the fields of astrophysics and planetary
science.

00:11:13.740 --> 00:11:18.660
But some of its capabilities will include:
directly observing exoplanets and searching

00:11:18.660 --> 00:11:24.209
for biosignatures, categorizing all the different
kinds of exoplanets out there, from hot Jupiters

00:11:24.209 --> 00:11:25.209
to super Earths.

00:11:25.209 --> 00:11:29.370
It’ll be able to observe objects within
the Solar System better than anything else

00:11:29.370 --> 00:11:34.379
- if we don’t have a spacecraft there, LUVOIR
will be a pretty good view.

00:11:34.379 --> 00:11:39.110
For example, here’s a view of Enceladus
from Hubble, compared to the view from LUVOIR.

00:11:39.110 --> 00:11:44.870
It will be able to look out anywhere in the
Universe, to see much smaller structures than

00:11:44.870 --> 00:11:45.870
Hubble.

00:11:45.870 --> 00:11:49.709
It’ll see the first galaxies, first stars,
and help measure the concentrations of dark

00:11:49.709 --> 00:11:52.680
matter across the Universe.

00:11:52.680 --> 00:11:56.839
Astronomers still don’t fully understand
what happens when stars gather enough mass

00:11:56.839 --> 00:11:58.019
to ignite.

00:11:58.019 --> 00:12:03.009
LUVOIR will look into star forming regions,
peer through the gas and dust and see the

00:12:03.009 --> 00:12:07.959
earliest moments of star formation as well
as the planets orbiting them.

00:12:07.959 --> 00:12:11.709
Have I got you totally and completely excited
about the future of astronomy?

00:12:11.709 --> 00:12:12.709
Good.

00:12:12.709 --> 00:12:14.199
But here’s comes the bad news.

00:12:14.199 --> 00:12:20.170
There’s almost no chance reality will match
this fantasy.

00:12:20.170 --> 00:12:24.499
Earlier this month NASA announced that mission
planners working on these space telescopes

00:12:24.499 --> 00:12:29.379
will need to limit their budgets to between
three and five billion dollars.

00:12:29.379 --> 00:12:33.740
Until now, planners didn’t have any guidelines,
they were to just design instruments that

00:12:33.740 --> 00:12:36.439
could get the science done.

00:12:36.439 --> 00:12:40.680
Engineers had been working on mission plans
that could easily cross $5 billion for HabEx,

00:12:40.680 --> 00:12:47.319
Lynx and OST, and were considering a much
larger $20 billion for LUVOIR.

00:12:47.319 --> 00:12:51.960
Even though Congress has been pushing for
surprisingly big budgets for NASA, the space

00:12:51.960 --> 00:12:54.769
agency wants its planners to be conservative.

00:12:54.769 --> 00:13:00.540
And when you consider just how over budget
and late James Webb has become, it’s not

00:13:00.540 --> 00:13:01.959
entirely surprising.

00:13:01.959 --> 00:13:07.769
James Webb was originally supposed to cost
between one and three point five billion dollars

00:13:07.769 --> 00:13:10.640
and launch between 2007 and 2011.

00:13:10.640 --> 00:13:16.740
Now it looks like 2020 for a launch, the costs
have broken past a Congress mandated $8.8

00:13:16.740 --> 00:13:20.350
billion budget, and it’s clear there’s
still a lot of work to be done.

00:13:20.350 --> 00:13:26.529
In a recent shake test, engineers found washers
and screws that had shaken out of the telescope.

00:13:26.529 --> 00:13:28.990
This isn’t like an IKEA shelf with leftover
parts.

00:13:28.990 --> 00:13:30.660
These pieces are important.

00:13:30.660 --> 00:13:36.819
Even though it’s been saved from the chopping
block, the WFIRST Telescope is estimated to

00:13:36.819 --> 00:13:40.029
be $3.9 billion, up from its original $2 billion
budget.

00:13:40.029 --> 00:13:45.600
One, two or maybe even all of these telescopes
will eventually get built.

00:13:45.600 --> 00:13:50.300
This is what the scientists think are most
important to make the next discoveries in

00:13:50.300 --> 00:13:55.420
astronomy, but get ready for budget battles,
cost overruns and stretching timelines.

00:13:55.420 --> 00:13:59.040
We’ll know better when all the studies come
together in 2019.

00:13:59.040 --> 00:14:05.060
It would take some kind of engineering miracle
to have all four telescopes come together,

00:14:05.060 --> 00:14:09.619
on time and on budget, to blast to space together
in 2035.

